 PCK> Yes.  It's reasonably easy to run the cipher backwards, and one
 PCK> can do this all the way to the beginning of the pseudorandom
 PCK> header.  The state at that point can then be used to decrypt
 PCK> other files encrypted with the same password.

 PCK> Although I haven't written code to do this yet, it should also
 PCK> be possible to keep going backward to find the text of shorter
 PCK> passwords.  (Longer passwords can't be determined uniquely since
 PCK> multiple passwords will lead to the same state.)

Well it seems to me that you don't need to find the actual
password, just any one of the "passwords" that leads to the same
state.  You would have an effective alternative password and who
cares what the original one was?
